{"title_page": "Caterpillar Inc.", "text_new": "{{short description|American corporation that sells machinery, engines, generator sets and financial products}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Caterpillar Inc.\n| logo = Caterpillar logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{ubl|{{NYSE|CAT}}|[[DJIA]] component|[[S&P 100]] component|[[S&P 500]] component}}\n| industry = [[Heavy equipment]]<br />Engines<br />[[Financial services]]\n| predecessor = [[C. L. Best]]<br />[[Holt Manufacturing Company]]\n| successor = \n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1925|04|15}}<br>[[California]], U.S.\n| founder = \n| defunct = \n| location = [[Deerfield, Illinois]], U.S.\n| locations = \n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = [[Jim Umpleby]] (chairman{{wbr}}&nbsp;& CEO)\n| products = {{Collapsible list\n  |framestyle=border:none; padding:0;\n  |title=<small>Products List</small>\n  |1=[[Caterpillar D11|D11 Bulldozer]]\n  |2=[[Caterpillar 345C L|345C L Excavator]]\n  |3=[[Caterpillar 930G|930G Wheel Loader]]\n  |4=[[Caterpillar 797F|797F Haul Truck]]\n  |5=[[Caterpillar C13|C13 Diesel Engine]]\n  |6=[[Caterpillar C32|C32 Diesel/Gasoline Engine]]\n  |7=[[Caterpillar C280|C280 Diesel/Gasoline Engine]]\n}}\n| services = {{Collapsible list\n  |framestyle=border:none; padding:0;\n  |title=<small>Services List</small>\n  |1=[[Financial services|Financing]]\n  |2=Insurance\n  |3=[[Maintenance, repair and operations|Maintenance]]\n  |4=[[Training]]\n}}\n| revenue = {{increase}} {{US$|54.7 billion|link=yes}} (2018)<ref name=\"2018SEC\">{{cite web|title=Caterpillar 2018 SEC Filing|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/18230/000001823018000042/cat_10-kx12312017.htm#s68ED144112675DA4AA05C4BE849D8235|publisher=sec.gov|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{increase}} {{US$|8.293 billion}} (2018)<ref name=\"2018SEC\"/>\n| net_income = {{increase}} {{US$|6.147 billion}} (2018)<ref name=\"2018SEC\"/>\n| assets = {{increase}} {{US$|78.509 billion}} (2018)<ref name=\"2018SEC\"/>\n| equity = {{increase}} {{US$|14.08 billion}} (2018)<ref name=\"2018SEC\"/>\n| owner = \n| num_employees = 101,500 (2018)<ref name=\"2017SEC\">{{cite web|title=Caterpillar 2017 SEC Filing|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/18230/000001823018000042/cat_10-kx12312017.htm#s68ED144112675DA4AA05C4BE849D8235|publisher=sec.gov|accessdate=22 February 2018}}</ref>\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = {{Collapsible list\n  |framestyle=border:none; padding:0;\n  |title=<small>Subsidiary List</small>\n  |1=Caterpillar Financial Services \n  |2=Caterpillar Insurance Holdings\n  |3=Caterpillar Logistics Services\n  |4=Caterpillar Marine Power Systems\n  |5=FG Wilson\n  |6=[[Perkins Engines]]\n  |7=[[Progress Rail Services]]\n  |8=[[Solar Turbines]]\n}}\n| footnotes = <ref name=about/><ref name=10K_2009/><ref name=\"haddock-37\">{{cite book\n| last1 = Haddock\n| first1 = Keith\n| last2 = Orlemann\n| first2 = Eric\n| editor = Paul Johnson\n| title = Classic Caterpillar Crawlers\n| url = https://archive.org/details/classiccaterpill0000hadd\n| url-access = registration\n| accessdate = 2010-11-06\n| date = 2001-11-11\n| publisher = MBI Publishing Company\n| location = St. Paul, Minnesota, United States\n| pages = [https://archive.org/details/classiccaterpill0000hadd/page/37 37]\u201338\n| isbn = 978-0-7603-0917-9\n}}</ref><ref name=4Q2010_Earnings>{{cite web \n |url=http://www.caterpillar.com/cda/files/2607135/7/Cat+Inc.+4Q2010+Final.pdf \n |title=Caterpillar Inc. 4Q 2010 Earnings Release \n |date=2011-01-27 \n |work=caterpillar.com \n |publisher=Caterpillar Inc. \n |pages=15, 36\u201337, 39 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wD7jfxmL?url=http://www.caterpillar.com/cda/files/2607135/7/Cat+Inc.+4Q2010+Final.pdf \n |archivedate=February 3, 2011 \n |accessdate=2011-02-02 \n |quote=Total sales and revenues....42,588 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=mdy \n }}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|caterpillar.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Caterpillar Inc.''' (sometimes shortened to '''CAT''') is an American [[Fortune 100]] corporation which designs, develops, engineers, manufactures, markets and sells [[Heavy equipment (construction)|machinery]], [[Internal combustion engine|engine]]s, [[Financial services|financial products]] and insurance to customers via a worldwide [[Dealer (franchising)|dealer]] network. Rain also brings caterpillar this has proved by a person of NASA i.e mr. hongshawani ho sahe. \nIt is the world's largest construction equipment manufacturer.<ref name=about>{{cite web \n |url=http://www.cat.com/about-cat \n |title=Caterpillar \u2013 About Cat \n |year=2010 \n |work=cat.com \n |publisher=Caterpillar Inc \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5o9n5nlXT?url=http://www.cat.com/about-cat \n |archivedate=March 11, 2010 \n |accessdate=2010-03-11 \n |quote=We deliver products, services and technologies in three principal lines of business: Machinery, Engines and Financial Products. \n |url-status=dead \n |df=mdy \n }}</ref><ref name=10K_2009>{{cite web |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/18230/000001823010000092/form10k_2009.htm |title=2009 Form 10-K |date=2010-02-19 |publisher=United States Securities and Exchange Commission |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5oSPRbeGV?url=http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/18230/000001823010000092/form10k_2009.htm |archivedate=March 24, 2010 |accessdate=2010-03-23 |quote=As of December 31, 2009, we employed 93,813 persons of whom 50,562 were located outside the United States. |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news \n |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune500/2009/snapshots/81.html \n |title=Fortune 500 2009: Top 100 American Companies \u2013 Caterpillar \u2013 CAT \n |first=Jia Lynn \n |last=Yang \n |date=2009-05-04 \n |work=FORTUNE on CNNMoney.com \n |publisher=Cable News Network, Inc \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5o9yKYxus?url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune500/2009/snapshots/81.html \n |archivedate=March 11, 2010 \n |accessdate=2010-03-11 \n |quote=Rank: 44 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=mdy \n }}</ref>\nIn 2018, Caterpillar was ranked #65 on the Fortune 500 list<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/fortune500/list/|title=Fortune 500 Companies 2018: Who Made the List|website=Fortune|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref> and #238 on the Global Fortune 500 list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/global500/list/|title=Fortune Global 500 List 2018: See Who Made It|website=Fortune|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref> Caterpillar [[stock]] is a component of the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.djaverages.com/index.cfm?view=industrial&page=components\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130122072213/http://www.djaverages.com/index.cfm?view=industrial&page=components\n |url-status = dead\n |archive-date = 2013-01-22\n |title      = Dow Jones Averages \u2013 Dow Jones Industrial Average \u2013 Components\n |year       = 2010\n |work       = djaverages.com\n |publisher  = Dow Jones & Company\n |accessdate = 2010-03-11\n |quote      = Ticker CAT \u2013 Company Name Caterpillar Incorporated\n}}</ref>\n\nCaterpillar Inc. traces its origins to the 1925 merger of the [[Holt Manufacturing Company]] and the [[C. L. Best|C. L. Best Tractor Company]], creating a new entity, the California-based Caterpillar Tractor Company.<ref name=lehman_deals>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.library.hbs.edu/hc/lehman/chrono.html?company=caterpillar_tractor_co \n |title=Caterpillar Tractor Co. List of Deals \n |year=2010 \n |work=Lehman Brothers Collection \n |publisher=President and Fellows of Harvard College \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629185404/http://www.library.hbs.edu/hc/lehman/chrono.html?company=caterpillar_tractor_co \n |archivedate=June 29, 2010 \n |accessdate=2010-11-06 \n |quote=In 1925 Holt and C.W. Best's company merged to form the Caterpillar Tractor Company. \n |url-status=dead \n |df=mdy \n}}</ref> In 1986, the company reorganized itself as a Delaware corporation under the current name, Caterpillar Inc. Caterpillar's headquarters are located in [[Deerfield, Illinois]]; it announced in January 2017 that over the course of that year it would relocate its headquarters from Peoria, Illinois, to Deerfield, Illinois, scrapping plans from 2015 of building an $800 million new headquarters complex in downtown Peoria.<ref name=PStar2017/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Yerak|first1=Becky|title=Caterpillar will move headquarters to Chicago area, citing transportation access|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-caterpillar-headquarters-chicago-0201-biz-20170131-story.html|accessdate=17 July 2017|work=The Chicago Tribune|date=31 Jan 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe company also licenses and markets a line of clothing and workwear boots under its Cat / Caterpillar name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catfootwear.com/US/en/contactus|title=Contact Us \u2013 CAT Footwear|publisher=}}</ref> \nCaterpillar machinery is recognizable by its trademark \"Caterpillar Yellow\" [[livery]] and the \"CAT\" logo.<ref name=tmyellow>{{cite web \n |url=http://www.cat.com/cda/layout?m=37321&x=7 \n |title=Caterpillar \u2013 Legal Notices \n |year=2010 \n |work=cat.com \n |publisher=Caterpillar Inc \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5o9o5qhpO?url=http://www.cat.com/cda/layout?m=37321&x=7 \n |archivedate=March 11, 2010 \n |accessdate=2010-03-11 \n |quote=\"Caterpillar Yellow,\"...trade dress...are trademarks of Caterpillar... \n |url-status=dead \n }}</ref>\n{{TOC limit|limit=3}}\n\n== History ==\n[[File:15-08-historischesRaupenfahrzeug IMG 1446.JPG|thumb|HOLT (before 1925)]]\n{{Main|Holt Manufacturing Company}}\n[[Image:BenjaminHolt.jpg|thumb|left|[[Benjamin Holt]], one of the founding fathers of [[Holt Manufacturing Company]].]]\n\n=== Origins ===\nThe steam tractors of the 1890s and early 1900s were extremely heavy, sometimes weighing {{convert|1000|lb}} per [[horsepower]], and often sank into the rich, soft earth of the [[Sacramento \u2013 San Joaquin River Delta|San Joaquin Valley Delta]] farmland surrounding [[Stockton, California]]. [[Benjamin Holt]] attempted to fix the problem by increasing the size and width of the wheels up to {{convert|7.5|ft}} tall and {{convert|6|ft}} wide, producing a tractor {{convert|46|ft}} wide. But this also made the tractors increasingly complex, expensive and difficult to maintain.\n\n[[File:Cat45-mojave.jpg|thumb|Two [[Holt tractor|Holt 45]] gas crawler tractors team up to pull a long wagon train in the [[Mojave Desert]] during construction of the [[Los Angeles Aqueduct]] in 1909.]]\nAnother solution considered was to lay a temporary [[plank road]] ahead of the steam tractor, but this was time-consuming, expensive, and interfered with earthmoving. Holt thought of wrapping the planks around the wheels. He replaced the wheels on a {{convert|40|hp}} Holt steamer, No. 77, with a set of wooden tracks bolted to chains. On Thanksgiving Day, November 24, 1904, he successfully tested the updated machine plowing the soggy [[Delta (landform)|delta land]] of [[Sacramento \u2013 San Joaquin River Delta|Roberts Island]].<ref name=\"laird\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wastehandling.com/ME2/Audiences/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications%3A%3AArticle&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&id=47C5DE563581487B9E4394B939909F9E&tier=4 |date=March 3, 2009 |title=Benjamin Holt (1849\u20131920): The Father of the Caterpillar tractor |first=Gwenyth Laird |last=Pernie |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120803071138/http://www.wastehandling.com/ME2/Audiences/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications%3A%3AArticle&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&id=47C5DE563581487B9E4394B939909F9E&tier=4 |archivedate=August 3, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nContemporaneously [[Richard Hornsby & Sons]] in Grantham, Lincolnshire, England, developed a steel plate tracked vehicle which it patented in 1904. This tractor steered by differential braking of the tracks and did not require the forward tiller steering wheel for steering making it the first to do so.  Several tractors were made and sold to operate in the Yukon, one example of which was in operation until 1927 remnants of which still exist to this day. However, Hornsby were unable to interest the British Military in 1907, although soldiers who witnessed the trials nicknamed the machine a caterpillar.  Hornsby therefore found a limited market for their tractor so they sold their patent to Holt in 1911, the same year Holt trademarked \"Caterpillar\".\n\nCompany photographer Charles Clements was reported to have observed that the tractor crawled like a [[caterpillar]],<ref name=\"about-inventors\">{{cite web|url=http://inventors.about.com/od/bstartinventions/a/bulldozer.htm |title=History of Bulldozers| first= Mary |last=Bellis|publisher= About.com |accessdate=2010-02-28 }}</ref> and Holt seized on the metaphor. \"Caterpillar it is. That's the name for it!\"<ref name=\"laird\" /> Some sources, though, attribute this name to British soldiers in July 1907. Two years later Holt sold his first steam-powered tractor crawlers for US$5,500, about US$128,000 today. Each side featured a track frame measured {{convert|30|in}} high by {{convert|42|in}} wide and were {{convert|9|ft}} long. The tracks were {{convert|3|in}} by {{convert|4|in}} [[Sequoia sempervirens|redwood]] slats.<ref name=\"laird\" />\n\nHolt received the first [[patent]] for a practical [[continuous track]] for use with a tractor on December 7, 1907, for his improved \"Traction Engine\" (\"improvement in vehicles, and especially of the traction engine class; and included endless traveling platform supports upon which the engine is carried\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kipnotes.com/AgriculturalMachinery.htm |title=Agricultural Machinery, Business History of Machinery Manufacturers |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017162514/http://www.kipnotes.com/AgriculturalMachinery.htm |archivedate=October 17, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n=== Initial Establishment in Peoria (1910) and Headquarters Move to Deerfield (2017) ===\n[[File:The Caterpillar Tractor Co. Factory, Peoria, Ill.jpg|thumb|A postcard showing the Caterpillar Tractor Co. plant in [[East Peoria|Peoria]], period 1930\u20131945.]]\n\nOn February 2, 1910,<ref name=acmoc2>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmoc.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=35&limit=1&limitstart=2 |title=Caterpillar History |accessdate=2010-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719235759/https://www.acmoc.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=35&limit=1&limitstart=2 |archivedate=July 19, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> Holt opened up a plant in [[East Peoria]], [[Illinois]], led by his nephew Pliny Holt. There Pliny met farm implement dealer [[Murray M. Baker|Murray Baker]] who knew of an empty factory that had been recently built to manufacture farm implements and steam [[traction engine]]s. Baker, who later became the first executive vice president of what became Caterpillar Tractor Company, wrote to Holt headquarters in Stockton and described the plant of the bankrupt Colean Manufacturing Co. of [[East Peoria, Illinois]].\nOn October 25, 1909, Pliny Holt purchased the factory,<ref name=leffingwell/> and immediately began operations with 12 employees.<ref name=\"gordon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allbusiness.com/company-activities-management/company-locations/13937416-1.html |title=Cat hits 100-year milestone: Holt Caterpillar started operations in East Peoria in 1910 with 12 employees|first= Paul |last=Gordon|publisher=Journal Star|location=Peoria, Illinois|date=February 16, 2010 |accessdate=2010-02-28 }}</ref> Holt incorporated it as the Holt Caterpillar Company, although he did not trademark the name ''Caterpillar'' until August 2, 1910.<ref name=\"acmoc2\"/>\n\nThe addition of a plant in the [[Midwest]], despite the hefty [[Capital (economics)|capital]] needed to retool the plant, proved so profitable that only two years later the company employed 625 people and was exporting tractors to [[Argentina]], Canada, and [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"idch\">{{Cite book| chapter-url = http://www.enotes.com/company-histories/caterpillar-inc/roots-late-19th-century-endeavors-best-holt | chapter = Caterpillar Inc: Roots in Late 19th-Century Endeavors of Best and Holt | title = International Directory of Company Histories | volume = 63 | publisher = [[St. James Press]] | location = [[Farmington Hills, Michigan]] | year = 2004 | isbn = 1-55862-508-9 | author = Jay P. Pederson, editor. }}</ref> Tractors were built in both Stockton and East Peoria.<ref name=\"orleman\">{{Cite book| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uq07avP69BgC&pg=PA8 | title = Caterpillar | first = Eric C. | last = Orleman | publisher = MBI Publishing Company | year = 2006 | pages = 8\u20139 | accessdate = July 13, 2009 | isbn=978-0-7603-2553-7}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Newly Incorporated|date=January 13, 1892 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 31, 2017, after more than 90 years of being headquartered in [[Peoria, Illinois]], the company announced plans to move their headquarters from Peoria to [[Chicago, Illinois]] by the end of 2017. The upper echelon of executives, including newly installed CEO Jim Umpleby, would begin relocating later that year, with up to 100 employees total moving by year's end. About 300 employees will work in the new office at an as-yet undecided location once the transition is complete. The company indefinitely suspended planning for the new Peoria headquarters in the fall of 2015 after announcing a restructuring effort that called for up to 10,000 jobs to be cut and about 20 facilities around the world to be closed or consolidated. The changes contributed to $2.3 billion in savings in 2016, but sales and revenue for last year still were more than 40 percent below peak levels of 2012. Umpleby said that decline is a fundamental reason the company's board of directors opted to move global headquarters to an area where the global marketplace is in easier reach.<ref name=PStar2017>{{cite news|last1=Buedel|first1=Matt|title=Caterpillar moving headquarters, CEO from Peoria to Chicago|url=http://www.pjstar.com/news/20170131/caterpillar-moving-headquarters-ceo-from-peoria-to-chicago|work=Peoria Journal Star|date=January 31, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe site finally selected at 500 Lake Cook Road in [[Deerfield, Illinois]] had for many years been the location of a [[Fiatallis]] facility producing wheel loaders.\n\n=== Use in World War I ===\n\nThe first tanks used in WW1 were manufactured by William Foster & Co. also in Lincolnshire and were introduced to the battlefield in 1916.  That company had collaborated with Hornsby in the development of the vehicles demonstrated to the British military in 1907, providing the paraffin (kerosene) engines.\n\nHolt's track-type tractors played a support role in World War I. Even before the U.S. formally entered WWI, Holt had shipped 1,200 tractors to England, France and Russia for agricultural purposes. These governments, however, sent the tractors directly to the battlefront where the military put them to work hauling artillery and supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.caterpillar.com/company/history |title=Caterpillar History | accessdate=2011-02-07}}</ref> When [[World War I]] broke out, the British War Office ordered a Holt tractor and put it through trials at [[Aldershot]]. The War Office was suitably impressed and chose it as a gun-tractor.<ref name=\"historic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.historicroadways.co.uk/s-007.htm |title=Holt Caterpillar |accessdate=2010-02-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204121517/http://www.historicroadways.co.uk/s-007.htm |archivedate=December 4, 2009 }}</ref> Over the next four years, the Holt tractor became a major [[artillery tractor]], mainly used to haul medium guns like the [[6 inch 26 cwt howitzer|6-inch howitzer]], the [[BL 60 pounder gun|60-pounder]], and later the [[BL 9.2 inch Howitzer|9.2-inch]] howitzer.<ref name=\"freeserver\">{{cite web| url=http://www.landships.freeservers.com/new_pages/holt_tractor_info.htm |title=The Holt 15-ton Tractor| accessdate=2011-02-26}}</ref>\n\nHolt tractors were also the inspiration for the development of the British [[tank]], which profoundly altered ground warfare tactics.<ref name=\"laird\"/><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.holtremix.com/company/history.asp |title=HOLT CAT \u2013 Texas Caterpillar Dealer Equipment Sales and Service| year=2007| accessdate=2010-02-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070419135813/http://www.holtremix.com/company/history.asp |archivedate=2007-04-19}}</ref> Major [[Ernest Dunlop Swinton|Ernest Swinton]], sent to France as an army [[war correspondent]], very soon saw the potential of a track-laying tractor.<ref name=swinton>{{Cite book|title=Eyewitness |first=Ernest|last=Swinton|authorlink= Ernest Dunlop Swinton|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I02-m4nZOa8C | isbn=978-0-405-04594-3 | year=1972 | publisher=Ayer Publishing}}</ref>{{rp|116}} Although the British later chose an English firm to build its first tanks, the Holt tractor became \"one of the most important military vehicles of all time.\"<ref name=\"freeserver\"/>\n\n[[File:Serpentine vtm cat d2 gnangarra.jpg|thumb|A [[Caterpillar D2]], introduced in 1938, at the Serpentine Vintage Tractor Museum, [[Serpentine, Western Australia]].]]\n\n=== Post-war challenges ===\n\nHolt tractors had become well known during [[World War I]]. Military contracts formed the major part of the company's production. When the war ended, Holt's planned expansion to meet the military's needs was abruptly terminated. The heavy-duty tractors needed by the military were unsuitable for farmers. The company's situation worsened when artillery tractors were returned from Europe, depressing prices for new equipment and Holt's unsold inventory of military tractors. The company struggled with the transition from wartime boom to peacetime bust. To keep the company afloat, they borrowed heavily.\n\n[[C. L. Best|C. L. Best Gas Tractor Company]], formed by Clarence Leo Best in 1910 and Holt's primary competitor, had during the war received government support enabling it to supply farmers with the smaller agricultural tractors they needed.<ref name=ohecat/><ref name=acmoc3>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmoc.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=35&limit=1&limitstart=3 |title=Caterpillar History |accessdate=2010-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719235730/https://www.acmoc.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=35&limit=1&limitstart=3 |archivedate=July 19, 2011 }}</ref> As a result, Best had gained a considerable market advantage over Holt by war's end. Best also assumed considerable debt to allow it to continue expansion, especially production of its new Best Model 60 \"Tracklayer\".\n\nBoth companies were adversely impacted by the transition from a wartime to a peacetime economy, which contributed to a nationwide [[Depression of 1920\u201321|depression]], further inhibiting sales. On December 5, 1920, 71-year-old Benjamin Holt died after a month-long illness.<ref name=acmoc3/><ref>{{Cite news|title=Pacific Rural Press|volume=100|number=24|date=December 11, 1920 }}</ref>\n\n=== Caterpillar company formed (1925)===\n[[File:Caterpillar-60, 1931.jpg|thumb|A 60-horsepower Caterpillar Sixty being used for road work in the [[Cibola National Forest]], [[New Mexico]], United States in 1931]]\n\nThe banks and bankers who held the company's large debt forced the Holt board of directors to accept their candidate, Thomas&nbsp;A.&nbsp;Baxter, to succeed Benjamin Holt. Baxter initially cut the large tractors from the company's product line and introduced smaller models focused on the agricultural market. When the [[Federal Aid Highway Act of 1921 (Phipps Act)|Federal Aid Highway Act of 1921]] funded a US$1 billion federal highway building program, Baxter began refocusing the company towards building road construction equipment.<ref name=leffingwell>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=a_HbnkbSVhoC&pg=PA60&lpg=PA60&dq=holt+model+120+tractor#v=onepage&q=holt%20model%20120%20tractor&f=false |title= Classic Farm Tractors: History of the Farm Tractor |first= Randy|last= Leffingwell| accessdate= | isbn=978-0-7603-0246-0 | year=1996 | publisher=Crestline Imprints}}</ref>{{rp|66}} Both companies also faced fierce competition from the [[Fordson tractor|Fordson]] company.\n\nBetween 1907 and 1918, Best and Holt had spent about US$1.5 million in legal fees fighting each other in a number of [[breach of contract|contractual]], [[trademark infringement|trademark]] and [[patent infringement]] lawsuits.<ref name=acmoc6>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmoc.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=35&limit=1&limitstart=6 |title=Caterpillar History |accessdate=2010-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719235829/https://www.acmoc.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=35&limit=1&limitstart=6 |archivedate=July 19, 2011 }}</ref> Harry H. Fair of the bond brokerage house of Pierce, Fair & Company of San Francisco had helped to finance C.&nbsp;L.&nbsp;Best's debt and Holt shareholders approached him about their company's financial difficulty. Fair recommended that the two companies should merge. In April and May 1925, the financially stronger C.&nbsp;L.&nbsp;Best merged with the market leader Holt Caterpillar to form the Caterpillar Tractor Co.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.tractordata.com/farm-tractors/tractor-brands/best/best-tractors.html |title =Best Tractor History|accessdate=2010-02-24}}</ref>\n\nThe new company was headquartered in San Leandro until 1930, when under the terms of the merger it was moved to Peoria.<ref name=gordon/> Baxter had been removed as CEO earlier in 1925, and Clarence Leo Best assumed the title of CEO, and remained in that role until October 1951.<ref name=ohecat>{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.ohe.cat.com/cda/layout?m=85360&x=7\n| title       = Caterpillar On-Highway Engines: About Us>History>Growth\n| year        = 2007\n| work        = ohe.cat.com\n| publisher   = Caterpillar Inc\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070804223846/http://ohe.cat.com/cda/layout?m=85360&x=7\n| archivedate = August 4, 2007\n| accessdate  = February 24, 2010\n| quote       =\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Caterpillar company consolidated its product lines, offering only five track-type tractors: the [[Holt tractor#2 Ton|2&nbsp;Ton]], [[Holt tractor#5 Ton|5&nbsp;Ton]], and [[Holt tractor#10 Ton|10&nbsp;Ton]] from the Holt Manufacturing Company's old product line and the {{nowrap|[[Caterpillar 30]]}} and {{nowrap|[[Caterpillar 60]]}} from the C.&nbsp;L.&nbsp;Best Tractor Co.'s former product line. The 10&nbsp;Ton and 5&nbsp;Ton models were discontinued in 1926. In 1928, the 2&nbsp;Ton was discontinued. Sales the first year were US$13 million. By 1929, sales climbed to US$52.8 million, and Caterpillar continued to grow throughout the [[Great Depression]] of the 1930s.\n\nCaterpillar adopted the [[diesel engine]] to replace gasoline engines. During [[World War II]], Caterpillar products found fame with the [[Seabees]], Construction Battalions of the [[United States Navy]], who built [[Aerodrome|airfields]] and other facilities in the [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theater of Operations]]. Caterpillar ranked 44th among United States corporations in the value of wartime military production contracts.<ref>[[Whiz Kids (Department of Defense)|Peck, Merton J.]] & [[Frederic M. Scherer|Scherer, Frederic M.]] ''The Weapons Acquisition Process: An Economic Analysis'' (1962) [[Harvard Business School]] p.619</ref> During the post-war construction boom, the company grew at a rapid pace and launched its first venture outside the U.S. in 1950, marking the beginning of Caterpillar's development into a [[multinational corporation]].\n\n=== Expansion in developing markets ===\n[[File:Sz\u00e9ll K\u00e1lm\u00e1n t\u00e9r - 2015.04.10 (1).JPG|thumb|CAT 323DL]]\nCaterpillar built its first Russian facility in the town of [[Tosno]], located near [[St. Petersburg, Russia]]. It was completed in 16 months, occupied in November 1999, and began fabricating machine components in 2000.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.americanmachinist.com/beyond-cutting-zone/caterpillar-manufacture-highway-trucks-russia | title = Caterpillar to Manufacture Off-Highway Trucks in Russia | author = Robert Brooks | date = November 6, 2011}}</ref> It had the first electrical substation built in the [[Leningrad Oblast]] since the Communist government was dissolved on December 26, 1991. The facility was built under harsh winter conditions, where the temperature was below \u221213&nbsp;\u00b0F (\u221225&nbsp;\u00b0C). The facility construction was managed by the [[Lemmink\u00e4inen Group]] located in [[Helsinki, Finland]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}\n\nThe $125M Caterpillar Suzhou, [[People's Republic of China]] facility, manufactures medium wheel loaders and motorgraders, primarily for the Asian market. The first machine was scheduled for production in March 2009. URS Ausino, in San Francisco, California, manages facility construction.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}\n\nCaterpillar has manufactured in [[Brazil]] since 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brasil.cat.com/cda/layout?m=273363&x=7|title=Caterpillar in Brazil|publisher=|accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref> In 2010 the company announced plans to further expand production of [[backhoe]] and small wheel loaders with a new factory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cat.com/cda/files/2259581/7/062910%20Caterpillar%20Announces%20Plans%20for%20New%20Manufacturing%20Facility%20in%20Brazil.pdf|title=Caterpillar Announces Plans for New Manufacturing Facility in Brazil|publisher=|accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCaterpillar has been manufacturing machines, engines and generator sets in India as well. Caterpillar has 3 facilities in India, which are in the states of Tamil Nadu (Thiruvallur & Hosur) and Maharastra (Aurangabad).    \n\n=== Acquisitions ===\n\nIn addition to increasing sales of its core products, much of Caterpillar's growth has been through acquisitions, including:\n\n<!-- Please input entries into the table chronologically by date of acquisition, most recent at the bottom -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Sortable table\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Company or Asset Acquired\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Acquired From\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Products\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| [[Trackson]]\n| Milwaukee, Wisconsin, United States\n| 1951\n|\n| [[Traxcavator]]s (tracked loaders) and pipelayers\n| \"Traxcavator\" became a Cat brand\n|-\n| Towmotor Corporation\n| Mentor, Ohio, United States\n| 1965<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catlifttruck.com/jkcm/default.aspx?pg=4828|title=Cat Lift Trucks : About Cat|publisher=|accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref>\n|\n| Forklifts\n| In 1992 became [[Mitsubishi Caterpillar Forklift America|Mitsubishi Caterpillar Forklifts]], a joint venture 80% owned by [[Mitsubishi]]<br>[https://case.edu/ech/articles/t/towmotor-corp/<!-- Encyclopedia of Cleveland History entry --> Pre-acquisition history]\n|-\n| [[Solar Turbines|Solar Division and Turbomach Division]]\n| San Diego, California, United States\n| 1981<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mysolar.cat.com/cda/layout?m=10683&x=7|title=Solar Turbines: About Solar|publisher=|accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref>\n| [[International Harvester|International Harvester Company]]\n| Industrial [[gas turbine]]s\n| Became [[Solar Turbines|Solar Turbines Incorporated]], a wholly owned subsidiary of Caterpillar Inc.\n|-